            text: 'The `loading="lazy"` attribute defers loading of images that are below the viewport. They only load when the user scrolls near them, reducing initial page load time and bandwidth. Use `loading="eager"` (default) for above-the-fold images, and `lazy` for everything below.',
            expandedText: '🔬 `loading="lazy"` uses the **Intersection Observer API** internally to defer network requests until the image is near the viewport threshold. For images above the fold (visible without scrolling), always use `loading="eager"` (the default) or omit the attribute. Lazy-loading above-the-fold images delays the **Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)** metric, which hurts Core Web Vitals scores.\n\n📖 The browser implements its own threshold — images typically start loading when they are a few hundred pixels below the viewport edge, not at the exact moment they become visible. For `<iframe>` elements, `loading="lazy"` defers the entire frame including all its subresources.',
            codeExample: '<!-- Above the fold — load immediately (default) -->\n<img src="hero.jpg" alt="Hero image" loading="eager">\n\n<!-- Below the fold — defer until near viewport -->\n<img src="article-photo.jpg" alt="Article photo" loading="lazy">\n\n<!-- Iframes also support lazy loading -->\n<iframe src="map.html" loading="lazy" title="Map"></iframe>',
            language: 'html',
