            animationStep: 4,
            heading: '<div> and <span>',
          icon: '📦',
            text: '`<div>` is a generic block container — no semantic meaning, just grouping. `<span>` is a generic inline container. Use them for styling hooks or JavaScript targets when no semantic element fits. Prefer semantic elements when possible.',
            expandedText: '📖 `<div>` and `<span>` have **no implicit ARIA role** — screen readers treat them as anonymous containers. Excessive `<div>` nesting (often called "div soup") makes DOM traversal, CSS selectors, and debugging harder without providing any semantic benefit.\n\n💡 The rule of thumb: reach for the most specific semantic element first. If no semantic element fits (e.g. a layout wrapper with no meaning), only then use `<div>`. `<span>` is appropriate for inline styling hooks when `<strong>`, `<em>`, `<code>`, or `<mark>` do not fit. Always ask: does this element communicate meaning beyond "a box"?',
