            heading: 'Custom list markers',
            text: 'CSS `list-style-type` changes bullet or number style. `list-style: none` removes markers entirely — used in navigation menus. The `::marker` pseudo-element styles the bullet directly. For custom emoji bullets, use `list-style-image` or a CSS `content` trick.',
            expandedText: '📜 Removing list markers with `list-style: none` in Safari combined with VoiceOver historically caused the browser to no longer announce the element as a list. The fix is to add `role="list"` to the `<ul>`. This is a **browser accessibility bug**, not a CSS spec issue, but it affects real users.\n\n✅ The `::marker` pseudo-element provides direct styling control over list bullets and numbers without JavaScript. `content` overrides the marker character, `color` and `font-size` adjust its appearance independently from the list item text. This is a modern replacement for the older pattern of hiding the default marker and using `::before` with `content`.',
            codeExample: '/* Remove bullets for nav menu */\nnav ul {\n  list-style: none;\n  padding: 0;\n  margin: 0;\n}\n\n/* Custom bullet color */\nul li::marker {\n  color: #3b82f6;\n  font-size: 1.2em;\n}\n\n/* Emoji bullet */\nul.checklist li::marker {\n  content: "✓ ";\n}',
            language: 'css',
