            animationStep: 4,
            icon: '🧠',
            heading: 'The full picture',
            text: 'With semantic HTML, browsers, search engines, and assistive technologies all understand your page structure — no CSS classes required for meaning. ARIA landmark roles map directly to HTML5 elements, giving screen reader users one-keystroke navigation. Search engines use the heading hierarchy and `<article>` boundaries to determine content relevance.',
            expandedText: '📖 The **ARIA landmark roles** map directly to HTML5 semantic elements: `<main>` = `role="main"`, `<nav>` = `role="navigation"`, top-level `<header>` = `role="banner"`, top-level `<footer>` = `role="contentinfo"`, `<aside>` = `role="complementary"`. Screen reader users navigate landmarks with a single keystroke.\n\n📖 Search engines use semantic structure to determine content hierarchy. The `<h1>` through `<h6>` outline, `<article>` boundaries, and `<aside>` exclusions all influence how content is indexed and ranked. Semantic markup is free SEO and accessibility that comes with correct element choice.',
            codeExample: '<header>…</header>\n<nav>…</nav>\n<main>\n  <article>…</article>\n  <aside>…</aside>\n</main>\n<footer>…</footer>',
            language: 'html',
            analogy: {
              icon: '🗺️',
              title: 'Step 5 — Full semantic layout: a well-organized newspaper',
              text: [
                'A well-laid-out newspaper has the masthead (header), a table of contents (nav), main stories (main + article), sidebars (aside), and the fine print (footer). Each section has a clear purpose.',
                'With semantic HTML, your page has the same clear structure — understandable by browsers, search engines, screen readers, and other developers reading your code.',
              ],
            },
