            expandedText: '📖 **Margin collapse** is one of the most confusing CSS behaviors. When two vertical margins touch (adjacent siblings or parent-child without padding/border separator), they collapse to the **larger** of the two values rather than adding together. This means `margin-bottom: 20px` on a paragraph and `margin-top: 30px` on the next produces 30px of space, not 50px.\n\n📖 Margin collapse only occurs vertically (top/bottom) for block elements in normal flow. It does not occur for flex children, grid items, floated elements, or absolutely/fixed positioned elements. Setting `overflow: auto` or `padding` on a parent prevents collapsing between parent and child margins.',
