            text: '`px` is absolute. `em` is relative to the parent\'s font-size. `rem` is relative to the root `<html>` font-size (usually 16px). `%` is relative to the parent\'s size. Use `rem` for font sizes, `px` for borders, `%` for widths.',
            expandedText: 'px is an absolute unit -- 1px is 1 physical (or logical) pixel. em is relative to the current element font-size: 1.5em on a 16px element equals 24px. rem is relative to the root html font-size -- consistent throughout the page, making it the preferred unit for spacing and typography.\n\n% is relative to the parent container size -- useful for fluid widths. vw/vh are 1% of the viewport width/height respectively. ch equals the width of the 0 character -- great for sizing text inputs (e.g. width: 30ch). Rule of thumb: use rem for font sizes and spacing, % or fr for layouts, px only for borders, shadows, or when you need exact pixel control.',
