          icon: '🌐',
            text: 'Without CSS, browsers apply their own default styles — usually Times New Roman at 16px. Every CSS reset or stylesheet you write is overriding these defaults. CSS resets remove all defaults to give a clean slate; normalizers like `normalize.css` make them consistent across browsers instead. Understanding defaults helps you override only what you actually need to change.',
            expandedText: '📖 **Browser default text styles** exist because the web began as an academic document system where serif fonts, heading hierarchy, and link styling mattered more than visual design. CSS resets (like `* { margin: 0; padding: 0 }`) remove these defaults entirely; normalizers (normalize.css) make them consistent across browsers.\n\n⚠️ Never override the root `font-size` with a fixed pixel value — doing so breaks users who have increased their system font size for accessibility. Set `font-size: 100%` on `<html>` (or omit it) to preserve the user\'s preference, then use `rem` units throughout.',
