            text: 'The event loop picks one macrotask from the queue, runs it to completion on the call stack, then drains the microtask queue fully, then the browser may render, then the loop picks the next macrotask. This cycle is called a "tick".',
            expandedText: '📜 `requestAnimationFrame(callback)` schedules a callback just **before the browser repaints** — typically 60 times per second (~16.6 ms). This is the correct tool for animation loops and visual updates: it synchronises with the display refresh rate, pauses automatically when the tab is backgrounded, and batches updates.\n\n📜 Unlike `setTimeout(fn, 16)`, `rAF` is guaranteed to fire before every paint frame. For heavy computation inside an animation loop, process a portion each frame and schedule the next chunk with `requestAnimationFrame` recursively. This keeps the UI responsive since the browser can paint between chunks rather than being blocked by one long synchronous computation.',
