            text: 'JavaScript has six primitive types: `string`, `number`, `boolean`, `null`, `undefined`, and `symbol`. They are immutable values — not objects — and are compared by value, so two strings with the same characters are always strictly equal. When you call methods on a primitive, JavaScript temporarily wraps it in an object and discards the wrapper.',
            expandedText: '⚠️ JavaScript has six **primitive types**: `string`, `number`, `boolean`, `null`, `undefined`, and `symbol`. Primitives are **immutable** — you cannot change the value `42` itself, only point a variable at a different number. They are compared **by value**, so two strings with the same characters are always strictly equal.\n\n📖 Unlike objects, primitives have no persistent properties. When you call `"hello".toUpperCase()`, JavaScript temporarily wraps the string in a `String` object to access the method, then discards the wrapper. This automatic **boxing** is invisible but explains why string methods work on primitive string literals without any explicit wrapping.',
            codeExample: 'let name = "Alice"      // string\nlet age = 25           // number\nlet active = true      // boolean\nlet nothing = null     // null\nlet missing            // undefined\nlet id = Symbol()      // symbol',
