            expandedText: '📖 The `typeof` operator returns a lowercase string describing the type of any expression without throwing an error — even for undeclared variables. This makes it safe for feature-detection guards like `typeof window !== "undefined"`. The result is always one of: `"string"`, `"number"`, `"boolean"`, `"undefined"`, `"symbol"`, `"bigint"`, `"function"`, or `"object"`.\n\n⚠️ The famous quirk is `typeof null === "object"` — a 30-year-old bug frozen in the language for backwards compatibility. Always use **strict equality** (`val === null`) to test for `null` explicitly, and never rely on `typeof` alone to rule it out when null is a valid possibility in your data.',
            codeExample: 'typeof "hello"     // "string"\ntypeof 42          // "number"\ntypeof true        // "boolean"\ntypeof undefined   // "undefined"\ntypeof null        // "object" ⚠️ quirk!',
