            expandedText: 'Python uses try/except ExceptionType as e: -- you can catch specific exception types and the else clause runs only if no exception was raised. JavaScript uses try/catch (e) -- there is no else clause and no typed catch (catch catches everything). To handle specific error types in JS, check e instanceof TypeError or e.message inside the catch block.\n\nBoth have finally which runs unconditionally -- for cleanup like closing connections. Python raise re-throws the current exception; JS uses throw. Custom exceptions in Python extend Exception; in JS you extend Error. Avoid empty except / catch blocks that swallow errors silently -- always log or re-throw.',
