    sections: [
      { id: 'intro', type: 'intro', steps: [] },
      {
        id: 'explanation',
        type: 'explanation',
        steps: [
          {
            animationStep: 0,
            icon: '🌐',
            heading: 'The client sends a request',
            text: 'Your browser (the client) sends an HTTP request to a server. It includes the method (`GET`, `POST`, etc.), the URL, headers (content type, auth token), and an optional body for POST/PUT. Before the request reaches the server it passes through DNS resolution, TCP handshaking, and TLS negotiation.',
            expandedText: '📖 Every web interaction starts with the **client** (browser, mobile app, or CLI) sending an **HTTP request** to a server. The request includes a **method** (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE), a **URL**, **headers** (content type, auth token, accepted encodings), and an optional **body** for POST/PUT.\n\n📖 The client has no direct connection yet — it must first pass through DNS resolution, TCP handshaking, and (for HTTPS) TLS negotiation. This multi-step setup explains why the **first request** is slower than subsequent ones, and why **connection reuse** (HTTP keep-alive, HTTP/2 multiplexing) is an important performance optimisation.',            analogy: {
              icon: '📬',
              title: 'Step 0 — Client sends request: posting a letter',
              text: [
                'Writing a letter, putting it in an envelope, dropping it in a postbox. The letter includes destination, return address, and message.',
                'An HTTP request has a destination (URL), a sender (browser with headers), and optional content (body).',
              ],
            },
          },
          {
            animationStep: 1,
            icon: '📤',
            heading: 'DNS resolution',
            text: 'DNS (Domain Name System) translates a human-readable domain like `api.example.com` into the IP address routers actually use to deliver packets. The lookup checks multiple caches in order — browser cache, OS cache, local resolver — before contacting upstream nameservers, so repeated requests for the same domain are nearly instant. A low DNS TTL enables fast failover during outages; a high TTL reduces lookup latency for stable services.',
            expandedText: '📖 **DNS** (Domain Name System) translates a hostname like `api.example.com` into an IP address (`203.0.113.42`) that routers use to forward packets. The lookup cascades: browser cache → OS cache → local DNS resolver → root nameservers → TLD nameservers → authoritative nameservers.\n\n📜 Each record has a **TTL** (time-to-live) controlling cache duration. A low TTL enables fast failover; a high TTL reduces lookup latency. **DNS prefetching** (`<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//api.example.com">`) tells the browser to resolve a domain in the background before a resource is requested, reducing perceived latency for third-party API calls.',            analogy: {
              icon: '📖',
              title: 'Step 1 — DNS resolution: looking up the phone book',
              text: [
                'You have a name but need a phone number. You look it up in a directory.',
                'DNS translates `example.com` into an IP address like `93.184.216.34`. The result is cached locally for faster future lookups.',
              ],
            },
          },
          {
            animationStep: 2,
            icon: '📥',
            heading: 'The server processes',
            text: 'The server receives the request and passes it through your application code (Node.js, Python Flask, etc.) which determines what to do — validate authentication, apply business logic, and typically query a database. The server then assembles a response with the appropriate status code, headers, and body. The entire processing time from receiving the request to sending the response is often called "server latency" or "time to first byte" (TTFB).',
            expandedText: '📜 **TCP** establishes a reliable connection via a **three-way handshake**: client sends SYN, server replies SYN-ACK, client sends ACK. Only after this can data flow. **HTTPS** adds a **TLS handshake** on top, negotiating encryption before any application data is sent.\n\n📖 **HTTP/2** multiplexes multiple request/response pairs over a single TCP connection, eliminating head-of-line blocking. **HTTP/3** replaces TCP with **QUIC** (UDP-based), combining transport and TLS handshakes into one round trip — important for mobile clients on high-latency networks. Most CDNs and servers support HTTP/2 by default today.',            analogy: {
              icon: '🏭',
              title: 'Step 2 — Server processes: the factory receiving the order',
              text: [
                'The factory receives your order, reads what was requested, locates stock, packages it, and hands it to the courier.',
                'The server receives the request, parses it, runs business logic or queries a database, assembles the response.',
              ],
            },
          },
          {
            animationStep: 3,
            icon: '📥',
            heading: 'Database query',
            text: 'The application queries the database (PostgreSQL, SQLite, etc.) with SQL statements and waits for the results before continuing. Database queries are often the largest contributor to server response time — poorly written queries, missing indexes, or N+1 query patterns can slow responses significantly. Always use parameterized queries (`$1`, `$2` placeholders) to pass user-supplied values safely, preventing SQL injection.',
            expandedText: '📖 An **HTTP request** has four parts: the **request line** (method + URL + HTTP version), **headers** (key-value metadata), a blank line, and an optional **body**. Common headers: `Content-Type` (body format), `Authorization` (bearer token), `Accept` (acceptable response formats), and `Cookie` (session data).\n\n⚠️ **HTTPS** encrypts the entire request — headers, body, and URL path — so eavesdroppers see only the hostname (from TLS SNI) and data volume. Sensitive data like API keys must never appear in URL query strings even over HTTPS — always use headers or a POST body where the content is encrypted and not logged in server access logs.',            analogy: {
              icon: '🗄️',
              title: 'Step 3 — Database query: checking the warehouse inventory',
              text: [
                'The factory worker checks the warehouse: is this item in stock?',
                'Most server responses require a database query. The server sends SQL, the database returns matching rows, the server shapes them into the response.',
              ],
            },
          },
          {
            animationStep: 4,
            icon: '🔄',
            heading: 'Response sent back',
            text: 'The server sends an HTTP response: a status code (200 OK, 404 Not Found), headers, and the body (`HTML`, `JSON`). The `Content-Type` header tells the browser how to parse the body. Caching headers like `Cache-Control` and `ETag` let the browser avoid redundant re-fetches for unchanged resources.',
            expandedText: '📖 An **HTTP response** has a **status line** (HTTP version + status code + reason), **headers** (Content-Type, Cache-Control, Set-Cookie, CORS headers), a blank line, and the **body** (HTML, JSON, binary). `Content-Type` tells the client how to parse the body.\n\n📖 **Caching headers** dramatically affect performance: `Cache-Control: max-age=3600` allows clients and CDNs to cache for one hour. `ETag` provides a fingerprint for conditional requests — the server can respond with `304 Not Modified` and no body when content has not changed. Well-designed caching reduces server load by orders of magnitude and improves perceived performance for repeat visitors.',            analogy: {
              icon: '📦',
              title: 'Step 4 — Response sent back: the parcel arrives',
              text: [
                'The courier delivers the package. The label says what is inside and you decide whether to keep it.',
                'The HTTP response contains a status code (200, 404, 500), headers, and a body (HTML, JSON). The browser parses and renders it.',
              ],
            },
          },
        ],
      },
      { id: 'playground', type: 'playground', steps: [] },
    ],
