            text: 'Use `extends` to constrain what types `T` can be — without a constraint, TypeScript assumes `T` is anything, so you cannot safely access any property on it. `<T extends { length: number }>` guarantees `T` has a `.length`, making `val.length` type-safe. The pattern `<K extends keyof T>` enables typed property lookup: `getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K]`.',
            expandedText: '⚠️ A **constraint** (`<T extends SomeType>`) limits which types can be substituted for `T`. Without a constraint, TypeScript assumes `T` can be anything — so you cannot safely access any property on it. Adding `extends { length: number }` tells TypeScript that `T` is guaranteed to have a `.length` property, making `val.length` type-safe.\n\n📖 `extends keyof T` is a particularly powerful constraint: `<T, K extends keyof T>` means "K must be one of T property names." This is how `getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K]` achieves typed property access — eliminating `any` in generic lookup utilities.',
            codeExample: 'function getLength<T extends { length: number }>(val: T): number {\n  return val.length\n}\n\ngetLength("hello")   // 5\ngetLength([1,2,3])   // 3',
