            expandedText: '✅ `git checkout -b feature/login` (or `git switch -c feature/login`) creates a new branch and switches to it in one command. Branch names are free-form strings — the `feature/`, `bugfix/`, `chore/` prefix convention communicates purpose at a glance in long branch lists. Branches are lightweight in Git — creating a branch just creates a new pointer to a commit, consuming negligible space and time. Delete branches freely without losing any history.\n\n📖 A branch is just a **named pointer** to a commit. When you commit on a branch, the pointer advances to the new commit. When you switch branches, Git updates the working directory to match the commit the branch points to. **`HEAD`** is the special pointer that tracks which branch you are currently on. `git log --oneline --graph --all` visualises the branch topology — which branches share history and where they diverged.',
            codeExample: '# New project\ngit init\n\n# Existing project\ngit clone https://github.com/user/repo.git',
