            expandedText: '📖 The most effective commit strategy is **small, frequent, focused commits** — each commit does one thing and the message describes what and why. Small commits are easier to review, easier to revert, and easier to cherry-pick (apply a specific fix to another branch). Commit when a logical unit of work is complete, even if the feature is not finished — `git stash` or draft PRs handle incomplete work.\n\n⚠️ The commit message **subject line** should complete the sentence "This commit will..." — "Add login form validation", "Fix null pointer in CartService", "Refactor API client to use axios". Avoid vague messages like "fix bug", "update files", or "WIP". Teammates reading `git log` on `main` months later should understand what each commit did from the subject alone. The body can explain the motivation and any non-obvious decisions.',
            codeExample: '# Create and switch to new branch\ngit checkout -b feature/navigation\n\n# List all branches\ngit branch',
