            animationStep: 4,
            icon: '🚀',
            heading: 'Push to remote',
            text: 'Push your branch to the remote repository so teammates can see it and you can open a pull request. The `-u` flag sets the upstream tracking so future pushes just need `git push`. After the PR is merged, pull the updated `main` and delete the merged branch locally.',
            expandedText: '📖 After a PR is merged, **update your local `main`** with `git checkout main && git pull`. Then delete the merged branch locally: `git branch -d feature/login`. The `-d` flag (lowercase) refuses to delete branches with unmerged changes as a safety net; `-D` forces deletion. Delete the remote branch via the GitHub UI or with `git push origin --delete feature/login`.\n\n📖 Starting the next feature from an up-to-date `main` minimises future merge conflicts. If your feature branch has been open for several days while `main` received new commits, **rebase onto `main`**: `git rebase origin/main` replays your commits on top of the latest `main`. This keeps the branch current and produces a clean history without merge commits. Push with `--force-with-lease` after a rebase (not `--force`) to safely update the remote branch.',
