            expandedText: '📜 **Already-tracked files** are not affected by `.gitignore` rules. If a file was committed before the ignore rule was added, Git continues tracking it. To stop tracking a file without deleting it from disk, run `git rm --cached path/to/file`. This stages a deletion of the file from the repository while leaving it in the working directory. Commit the deletion along with the updated `.gitignore` rule, and future changes to the file will be ignored.\n\n📜 A common scenario: a developer accidentally commits `.env` before adding it to `.gitignore`. The correct remediation is `git rm --cached .env` followed by adding `.env` to `.gitignore` and committing. Then rotate all secrets that were in the file — they have been exposed in the history. If the repository is private and access is controlled, the risk is lower, but if the repository ever becomes public or access is compromised, all committed secrets must be considered exposed.',
